<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="p1-c1-s2-coefficients"><title> Coefficients </title>

	<p>
		In a differential equation, <term>coefficient</term> are the constants or functions that multiply the dependent variable or its derivatives. These coefficients play a critical role in determining the equation's behavior and the methods we use to solve it.
	</p>

	<p>
		Let's consider the differential equation:
	</p>

	<men xml:id="coefficients-example-10">
		y'' - 3y' + 2y = 0.
	</men>

	<p>
		Here, the coefficients are:
		<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ul{y''\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>\ul{y' \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>\ul{y  \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m> 1</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>-3</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m> 2</m></cell><cell/>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</p>

	<p>
		Coefficients can vary significantly across equations. They may be constants, as in the equation above, or functions of the independent variable. For example:
	</p>

	<men xml:id="coefficients-example-2">
		t^2 y'' + 5t y' + 6y = \sin(t).
	</men>

	<p>
		In this equation:
		<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ul{y''\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>\ul{y' \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>\ul{y  \text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m> t^2</m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>5t	 </m></cell><cell/>
				<cell><m>6	 </m></cell><cell/>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</p>

	<p>
		As you will see later, the nature of the coefficients will impact the equation's classification and solution techniques.
	</p>

	<example xml:id="c1-s2-3-ex1">
		<statement>
			<p>
				Identify the terms and coefficients in the equation
				<me>
					3t^2\ z' - 4\cos t + \frac{z'z}{t} - 515 z = -7.
				</me>
				
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				Note, the dependent variable in this equation is <m>z</m>. Since the <m>- 4\cos t</m> and <m>-7</m> do not contain <m>z</m>, they can be combined as a single constant term on the right-hand side of the equation, like so
				<me>
					3t^2 z' + \frac{1}{t} z'z - 515 z = 4\cos t - 7.
				</me>
				So the terms and coefficients are as follows:
				<tabular halign="center">
					<row>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'\text{ term}}</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'z\text{ term}}</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ul{z\text{ term}}</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ul{\text{constant term}}</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} 3t^2 z'</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ds\frac{1}{t} z'z</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} -515 z</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ds 4\cos t - 7</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<row>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ul{z'z\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ul{z\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell><cell/>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} 3t^2</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ds\frac{1}{t}</m></cell><cell/>
						<cell><m>\ds\vphantom{\frac11} -515</m></cell><cell/>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</p>
		</solution>
		
	</example>

	<p>
		As we progress, understanding the role of coefficients will help us choose the right approach to solving differential equations, whether they are constant-coefficient or variable-coefficient equations.
	</p>

	<xi:include href="./chkpts-3-coeffs.ptx" />

</subsection>